com.poesys.db.pk

Class GuidPrimaryKey

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.poesys.db.pk.AbstractPrimaryKey
      • com.poesys.db.pk.AbstractSingleValuedPrimaryKey
        • com.poesys.db.pk.GuidPrimaryKey
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IPrimaryKey, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<IPrimaryKey>, java.lang.Iterable<AbstractColumnValue>

    public class GuidPrimaryKey
extends AbstractSingleValuedPrimaryKey
    Implements the IPrimaryKey interface for a key constructed from a single GUID value as a string. The structure and semantics of the GUID key are the same as the sequence primary key except that the internal data type is a UUID, not a BigInteger, and the GUID is generated by this class, not by the database. The GUID representation in the database is a 36-character string.
    Author:
    Robert J. Muller

    • Method Detail

      • setParams

        public int setParams(java.sql.PreparedStatement stmt,
                     int nextIndex)
              throws java.sql.SQLException
        Description copied from interface: IPrimaryKey

        Set the key values as parameter values into a JDBC PreparedStatement. You must have already prepared the statement with SQL parameterized with the correct number of question marks. The method returns the next index available for value setting, which you can use to set any remaining parameters in the SQL statement. The parameters are set in the correct order (alphabetical order).

        The setInsertParams method does the same thing as this method but only for the primary key of the object being inserted. Use setParams for setting foreign keys into the INSERT statement.

        Specified by:
        setParams in interface IPrimaryKey
        Overrides:
        setParams in class AbstractSingleValuedPrimaryKey
        Parameters:
        stmt - the prepared statement; you must have already prepared the statement with a parameterized SQL statement
        nextIndex - the parameter index at which to start setting the primary key values
        Returns:
        the next index at which to set values
        Throws:
        java.sql.SQLException - when there is a problem setting the parameter value

      • getValueList

        public java.lang.String getValueList()
        Description copied from interface: IPrimaryKey

        Get a list of values suitable for inclusion in an error message in the format 

         
 " (col1=value[,col2=value]...)"
        where col1, col2, ... are the column names of the primary key and the values are the current values or "null" if there is no value. Note that there should be no blanks, line returns, or null characters in the string. The column names appear in the string in the correct order (alphabetical order).
        Returns:
        a list of values suitable for embedding in an error message
